{{about|the settlement in Canada's far north|the summer camp owned by YMCA in the United States|Camp Hazen YMCA}} {{Infobox settlement |name = Hazen Camp |settlement_type = Shelter <!-- Location ------------------> |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name = Canada |subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Territory]] |subdivision_name1 = [[Nunavut]] |subdivision_type2 = Region |subdivision_name2 = [[Qikiqtaaluk Region]] <!-- Population -----------------------> |population_total = 0 <!-- General information ---------------> |timezone = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]] |utc_offset = -5 |timezone_DST = EDT |utc_offset_DST = -4 |coordinates = {{coord|81|49|15.22|N|71|21|14.11|W|display=inline}} }} '''Hazen Camp''' is a shelter maintained and operated by [[Parks Canada]]. It contains many all-weather shelters for the park staff. The visiting researchers set up tents in the camp area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ernst|first1=Crystal|title=Final report for field season 2010|url=https://northernbiodiversity.wordpress.com/tag/lake-hazen/|website=Northern Biodiversity Program|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> Its coordinates are 81°49'15.22'N 71°21'14.11'W <ref>Google Earth</ref>
==History== Hazen Camp was originally established in 1957-1958 for [[Operation Hazen]]. It was one of the most comprehensive science research projects ever in the Canadian High Arctic.<ref name=Hazen>{{cite web|last1=Panchen|first1=Zoe|title=Introducing Lake Hazen|url=http://arcticplantphenology.blogspot.ca/2013/08/introducing-lake-hazen.html|website=Plant Phenology|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref> Today, Hazen Camp is used as an Warden Station and an access point to [[Quttinirpaaq National Park]].<ref name=Quttinirpaaq>{{cite web|title=Quttinirpaaq National Park of Canada Cultural Heritage|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/eng/pn-np/nu/quttinirpaaq/natcul/natcul6.aspx|website=Parks Canada|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>
==Geography== Hazen Camp is situated half way along the north shore of [[Lake Hazen]]. The closest settlement is [[Tanquary Fiord]]. McGill [[Mountain]] is very close to the station, rising 1000m into the sky.
==Notes== {{reflist}}
==External links== * [http://sis.agr.gc.ca/cansis/publications/surveys/nt/nt64-1/nt64-1_report.pdf Operation Hazen Characteristics of Soils of the Hazen Camp Area (1963)] {{Arctic Cordillera}} {{Subdivisions of Nunavut}}
[[Category:Extreme points of Earth]] [[Category:Ellesmere Island]] [[Category:Populated places in Arctic Canada]] [[Category:Populated places in the Qikiqtaaluk Region]]

The '''Fernandezian Region''' is a [[Floristic Region]] which includes two island groups, the [[Juan Fernández Islands]] and [[Desventuradas Islands]] [[archipelagos]], that lie in the [[South Pacific Ocean]] off the west coast of [[Chile]]. It is in the [[Antarctic Floristic Kingdom]], but often also included within the [[Neotropic ecozone|Neotropical Kingdom]].
[[Endemism|Endemic]] [[Family (biology)|plant families]] include [[Lactoridaceae]], with many endemic plant and animal [[genus|genera]] are found here too.
==References== * Takhtajan, Armen, 1986. ''Floristic Regions of the World''. (translated by T.J. Crovello & A. Cronquist). University of California Press, Berkeley.
